{
  "doc_id": "268",
  "text": "Orchidaceae, one of the largest plant families [CITATION_1] , share an unusual mode of germination. Their minutesized seeds are almost devoid of reserves and the undifferentiated embryo relies on a fungus, usually a basidiomycete, not only for its water and mineral needs but also for its carbon supply [CITATION_2] . The fungus penetrates the cells and forms hyphal coils that feed the plant, allowing a heterotrophic growth called 'mycotrophy' or 'myco-heterotrophy' [CITATION_3] . During further development, seedlings usually become autotrophic. However, some species remain achlorophyllous and myco-heterotrophic at the adult stage. Myco-heterotrophy is also described from some Ericaceae [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] and Gentianaceae [CITATION_7] , but there are more myco-heterotrophic species among orchids than in any other family [CITATION_8] .",
